The Era of Free International Order
The Cambrian period - Many analysts believe that the era of free international order ended with China's rise and Donald Trump's presidency.
But should he try to revive it if Joe Biden beats Trump in the November election?
Perhaps the result is not like that, but he must find an alternative.
Critics argue that the post-1945 American order was neither globally applicable nor always very free.
It will exclude more than half of the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and include many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is always exaggerated.
Even so, the strongest countries must lead in creating global public goods, otherwise they cannot be provided — and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
The Biden administration's realistic goal should be to establish an international system based on rules, with different member states participating in different affairs.
Will China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and 2000s, neither country could balance with the power of the United States, and the United States dominated and was obsessed with the pursuit of free values.
The United States bombed Yugoslavia and invaded Iraq without ever receiving a United Nations Security Council approval.
It also supports a "responsibility to protect" resolution adopted by the UN General Assembly in 2005, which aims to provide protection for citizens who are treated cruelly by their own government — the US later used this principle in 2011 to justify bombing Libya in order to protect civilians in Benghazi.
Critics describe this record as American hubris in the post-Cold War era — for example, when NATO's intervention in Libya ultimately led to regime change, Russia and China felt deceived — while its defenders describe it as the natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Regardless, China and Russia's growing power have more strictly limited freedom of interventionism actions.
So what's left then?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereignty principle as stipulated in the UN Charter, which stipulates that a state can only resort to war in self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, it has been extremely rare for a country to occupy a neighbor's territory by force, and once it happens, it will come at a high price due to sanctions, just like what happened in 2014 when Russia annexed Crimea.
In addition, the Security Council has frequently authorized the deployment of peacekeeping forces in countries in distress, and political cooperation has also successfully limited the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This rule-based order dimension remains crucial.
Specifically to economic relationships, the world needs to revise the rules.
Even before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism had already underpinned an unfair mercantilist model, which distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result would lead to a global decoupling of the supply chain, especially in situations where national security is threatened.
Despite China's complaints that the US is preventing companies like Huawei from building 5G networks in the West, the US stance is consistent with its demand for sovereignty.
After all, China blocked Google, Facebook and Twitter's operation in China for security reasons.
Negotiations on new trade rules will help prevent a further decoupling.
At the same time, despite the outbreak of the current crisis, cooperation in key financial fields remains extremely strong.
On the contrary, mutual dependence in the ecological field poses insurmountable obstacles in the face of sovereign states, as threats are transnational.
Regardless of how economic globalization is battered, environmental globalization will continue, as it is subject to biological and physical laws, while contemporary geopolitics has no effect on it.
These problems threaten everyone, but no country has the ability to solve them on its own.
In issues such as the 2019 novel coronavirus pandemic and climate change, power also has a so-called positive and constructive dimension.
Under such a premise, merely thinking about exercising power over others is not enough.
We must also ponder this from the dimension of exercising power in conjunction with other countries.
The Paris climate agreement and the World Health Organization have helped us and others.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite ideological differences, it did not affect cooperation between China and the US.
Biden faces the challenge of whether the US and China can cooperate to produce global public goods while engaging in competition in the traditional sphere of great power rivalry.
The Internet is a new and important issue — — because it has partial transnational characteristics, but at the same time it is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has already been partially divided.
Rules for internet freedom and privacy can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian countries.
As the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace suggests, if authoritarians wish to achieve connectivity, then some rules limiting interference with the underlying structure of the internet are also in their interests.
However, when they use surrogates to wage informational warfare or intervene in elections (such practices violate sovereignty), they must strengthen norms with rules such as those negotiated by the United States and the Soviet Union during the Cold War, such as the Hague Convention, to escalate maritime incidents, despite the continued ideological hostility.
The United States and like-minded countries must publicly declare which norms they are committed to upholding and establish the necessary deterrence.
Advocating for the free values of cyberspace does not mean the unilateral disarmament of the United States.
On the contrary, the United States should treat publicly permitted soft power and secret information warfare as soft and hard power respectively, and when the other side launches a secret information warfare, the United States should definitely counterattack.
Russian and Chinese programs and broadcasts can be allowed to be played openly, but secretly coordinating on social media etc. is not allowed.
In addition, the United States will continue to criticize the human rights records of these countries.
A recent poll shows that the American public wants to avoid military intervention, but does not want to withdraw from the alliance or multilateral cooperation.
Moreover, the public still values their values.
If Biden is elected, the problems he faces are not whether to restore a free international order.
The question is whether the US can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights while also working with a broader range of countries to manage the need for rule-based international institutions to address cross-border threats from climate change, pandemics, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
